Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[West Nile virus (WNV) is endemic in the lower 48 states of the USA, including Mississippi. Last year (2021), 7 human WNV infections occurred in the state. Of these, 4 were neuroinvasive and 3 were non-neuroinvasive (see https://www.cdc.gov/westnile/statsmaps/preliminarymapsdata2021/disease-cases-state-2021.html). Occurrence of human cases of WNV in the state is not surprising, but this case is very early in the usual transmission season. The WNV transmission season in the southern states in the USA usually occurs in the summer months, but cases can occur at any time as noted in the above report.

Since its introduction into the USA in 1999, annual case numbers in given states have been variable. Vector control and public education to avoid mosquito bites are the best measures to prevent human cases. Equine animals can be vaccinated, but there is no commercially available vaccine for human use. - Mod.TY

